{"runId":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro@2026-05-13T15-25-00-785Z","slug":"the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions","locale":"fr","model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T15:26:05.413Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2025-01-01--the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2025-01-01--the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions/fr/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/the-unassuming-power-of-multiple-choice-questions/fr/qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro/2026-05-13T15-25-00-785Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"caa10164f80350a5733ad5c3d7edf12b50afa0765cd3d9f8fd3c5758259550be","outputHash":"d7a5d6298b19f6be06edd7001b0401be7264b609e0093d57943c6b3cf9bbede4","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that multiple-choice questions (MCQs) are a powerful yet underappreciated tool for teaching, particularly in technical fields like programming, by leveraging *intentional distractors* to surface and address learners' misconceptions. It emphasizes that effective MCQs require crafting wrong answers that reflect real, common errors (e.g., syntax from other languages, legacy patterns), which act as a \"curriculum\" to reveal learners' mental models and guide instruction. Using a PostgreSQL example, it illustrates how a single question can serve multiple pedagogical goals across expertise levels, from basics to cross-platform precision. The tone is analytical and reflective, framed as a lesson learned by the author through quiz-building experience. Key metaphors include \"the distractor is the curriculum\" and MCQs as a feedback loop that demands instructional honesty from the author.","totalInputTokens":5509,"totalOutputTokens":4337,"totalCacheReadTokens":0,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":45298,"totalCostUsd":0.0014815999999999998,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3-